During six months, the Pope suspended the sentence, to the intent that the Monks might, if they

pleased, appear and shew cause against it. Their poverty incapacitated them from making their delence, and, as it is said, a sentence was prononnced, by which they

were expelled 3 but it is by no means cer- tain that they were legally abolished or sup·

pressed, as pleaded by the Canons. The hood and the amice replaced frock and

cowl. The Canons were installed: and, the better to efface all recollection of the former inmates, Bishop Hugh pulled down the conventual buildings, and rebuilt them upon a new plan, paying the expences with the moveable goods of the late community.

It appears, however, from the pleadings on the roll, that the Monks kept together as a body, notwithstanding their expulsion3 nor was any legal objection talren by the Court against their corporate existence. Similar examples may be found in modern

times, the Monks of La Trappe and the Nuns of Syon having, though despoiled of their possessions, equally withstood the
